31","1314–1352":"1314–1352","1314":"1314","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1331":"1331","Abt 1352":"circa 1352","1298":"1298","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","Abt 1345":"circa 1345","1380":"1380","1328":"1328","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Drakelow, Burton-Upon-Trent, Derbyshire, England":"Burton upon Trent St Modwen, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gresley, Drakelow, Derbyshire, England":"Drakelow, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Morton, Derbyshire, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, England","Colton, Staffordshire, England":"Colton, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"1328–1395":"1328–1395","1325–1350":"1325–1350","1345–1380":"1345–1380","1298–1331":"1298–1331","1314–1352":"1314–1352","1314":"1314","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1331":"1331","Abt 1352":"about 1352","1298":"1298","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","Abt 1345":"about 1345","1380":"1380","1328":"1328","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Drakelow, Burton-Upon-Trent, Derbyshire, England":"Burton upon Trent St Modwen, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Gresley, Drakelow, Derbyshire, England":"Drakelow, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Morton, Derbyshire, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, England","Colton, Staffordshire, England":"Colton, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gresley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Greasley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Greasley","meanings":["1  English: locative name, usually from Greasley (Notts) but possibly also from Gresley (Derbys). Some of the following early bearers may alternatively belong under (2), particularly the Lancs examples.","2  Norman, English: nickname, either from Old French  <i>greslet</i> ‘marked as by hail’, i.e. pitted or pock-marked, or Old French  <i>greslet</i>,  <i>gresli</i>,  <i>grailet</i> ‘thin, slim’. In early forms, the nickname has sometimes been confused with the place-name in (1).  Compare  Le Gresley   in Jersey and  <b>Greslé</b>,  <b>Grêlé</b> in France."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Gresley was born in 1328, in Morton, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Geoffrey Gresley, was 30 and his mother, Margaret Gernon, was 15. He married Alice Swynnerton. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1395, in Drakelow, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1328–1395":"1328–1395","1325–1350":"1325–1350","1345–1380":"1345–1380","1298–1331":"1298–1331","1314–1352":"1314–1352","1314":"1314","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1331":"1331","Abt 1352":"umbes 1352","1298":"1298","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","Abt 1345":"umbes 1345","1380":"1380","1328":"1328","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Drakelow, Burton-Upon-Trent, Derbyshire, England":"Burton upon Trent St Modwen, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gresley, Drakelow, Derbyshire, England":"Drakelow, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Morton, Derbyshire, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, England","Colton, Staffordshire, England":"Colton, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"1328–1395":"1328–1395","1325–1350":"1325–1350","1345–1380":"1345–1380","1298–1331":"1298–1331","1314–1352":"1314–1352","1314":"1314","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1331":"1331","Abt 1352":"noin 1352","1298":"1298","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","Abt 1345":"noin 1345","1380":"1380","1328":"1328","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Drakelow, Burton-Upon-Trent, Derbyshire, England":"Burton upon Trent St Modwen, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gresley, Drakelow, Derbyshire, England":"Drakelow, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Morton, Derbyshire, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, En